      <h1>Swami Vivekanand ji Biography (Struggle in life year wise with financial condition)</h1>
    </header>

    <section>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>1884:</strong> Swami Vivekananda's father died suddenly. He was only 21. His family became very poor and had no steady income.<br>
          <span class="financial">Financial Condition:</span> Very bad – they often had no food to eat.
        </li>
    
        <li>
          <strong>1885:</strong> He started spending more time with his spiritual teacher, Ramakrishna, while trying to support his family.<br>
          <span class="financial">Financial Condition:</span> Still very poor – struggled to manage both home and spiritual life.
        </li>
    
        <li>
          <strong>1886:</strong> Ramakrishna passed away. Vivekananda and other followers became monks. He left home and lived with very little.<br>
          <span class="financial">Financial Condition:</span> Very poor – lived on small donations and food from others.
        </li>
    
        <li>
          <strong>1887:</strong> He started traveling across India to learn about the country and help people. He had no money and faced many hardships.<br>
          <span class="financial">Financial Condition:</span> Almost nothing – lived like a wandering monk.
        </li>
    
        <li>
          <strong>1888–1892:</strong> Continued walking across India. He saw people suffering from poverty and became determined to help the nation.<br>
          <span class="financial">Financial Condition:</span> Very poor – often slept on streets or in temples.
        </li>
    
        <li>
          <strong>1893:</strong> He went to America to speak at the Parliament of Religions in Chicago. He had no money for the journey but got help from kind people.<br>
          <span class="financial">Financial Condition:</span> Poor – borrowed money and struggled when he arrived in the US.
        </li>
    
        <li>
          <strong>1894–1896:</strong> He became famous in the West and gave many lectures. He earned some money but lived simply to support his mission.<br>
          <span class="financial">Financial Condition:</span> A little better – could manage basic needs.
        </li>
    
        <li>
          <strong>1897:</strong> Returned to India and started the Ramakrishna Mission to serve the poor and spread education.<br>
          <span class="financial">Financial Condition:</span> Basic – used most of his funds for public service.
        </li>
    
        <li>
          <strong>1898–1902:</strong> Continued working hard, even though his health was weak. He focused on building the mission and training others.<br>
          <span class="financial">Financial Condition:</span> Modest – managed enough to keep the mission running.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </section>
